#: ../../../admin-guide/ext4.rst:52
msgid ""
"When comparing performance with other filesystems, it's always important to "
"try multiple workloads; very often a subtle change in a workload parameter "
"can completely change the ranking of which filesystems do well compared to "
"others.  When comparing versus ext3, note that ext4 enables write barriers "
"by default, while ext3 does not enable write barriers by default.  So it is "
"useful to use explicitly specify whether barriers are enabled or not when "
"via the '-o barriers=[0|1]' mount option for both ext3 and ext4 filesystems "
"for a fair comparison.  When tuning ext3 for best benchmark numbers, it is "
"often worthwhile to try changing the data journaling mode; '-o "
"data=writeback' can be faster for some workloads.  (Note however that "
"running mounted with data=writeback can potentially leave stale data exposed "
"in recently written files in case of an unclean shutdown, which could be a "
"security exposure in some situations.)  Configuring the filesystem with a "
"large journal can also be helpful for metadata-intensive workloads."
msgstr ""

